In _Java_, the _[int](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/nutsandbolts/datatypes.html)_ _data-type_ utilizes a _32-bit_ _[container](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Call_stack)_, reserving a bit for a signum, when negative.\
The maximum value, would be _2&lt;sup&gt; 31&lt;/sup&gt; &amp;minus; 1_, or _2,147,483,647_.\
_[Integer (Java SE 21 &amp;amp; JDK 21) &amp;ndash; MAX_VALUE](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/Integer.html#MAX_VALUE)_.

The typical solution here, is to use the _[BigInteger](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/math/BigInteger.html)_ _class_, which provides an unlimited accuracy.

Here is an example.

```java
List&lt;String&gt; generate(String a, String b) {
    BigInteger x = new BigInteger(a), y = new BigInteger(b), i = x;
    List&lt;String&gt; list = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
    int w = Math.max(a.length(), b.length());
    String f = &quot;%0&quot; + w + &quot;d&quot;;
    while (i.compareTo(y) &lt;= 0) {
        list.add(f.formatted(i));
        i = i.add(BigInteger.ONE);
    }
    return list;
}
```

